<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38150a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38150a">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38150a"> 150(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pianostrings / respond to different / vowels when loud / pedal is pressed</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Heimholtz had previously observed that a <mark>piano with the loud pedal pressed</mark> down would naturally <mark>repeat many of the vowel sounds</mark> which were sung to it &mdash; various strings resounding to the various musical components which together make up the intoned vowel. <small> Sir Richard Paget, <a name="RPHS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RPHS"><cite title="source">Human Speech Some Observations &amp;c.</cite></a> (1930) 27</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c08010c" href="c08all.htm#c08010c">VI.C.08:010(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
